Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements
Note 1.  Description of Business
Ascena Retail Group, Inc. (Ascena or the Company) is a leading national specialty retailer of apparel for women and tween girls operating, through its wholly owned subsidiaries, the , , and brands.  The Company operates (through its subsidiaries) over 2,500 stores throughout the United States, Puerto Rico and Canada, with annual revenues of over $2.9 billion.
dressbarn
maurices
Justice
The Company classifies its businesses into three segments following a brand-oriented approach: , and .  The segment includes approximately 836 specialty retail and outlet stores, as well as an e-commerce operation that was launched in the first quarter of Fiscal 2011.  The brand primarily attracts female consumers in the mid-30s to mid-50s age range and offers moderate-to-better quality career and casual fashion to the working woman. The segment includes approximately 797 specialty retail and outlet stores, and e-commerce operations.  The brand offers up-to-date fashion designed to appeal to the 17 to 34 year-old female, with stores concentrated in small markets (approximately 25,000 to 100,000 people).  The segment includes approximately 917 specialty retail and outlet stores, e-commerce operations, and certain licensed franchises in international territories.  The brand offers fashionable apparel to girls who are ages 7 to 14 in an environment designed to match the energetic lifestyle of tween girls.
dressbarn
maurices
Justice
dressbarn
dressbarn
maurices
maurices
Justice
Justice
Note 2.  Basis of Presentation
Segment Information
Historically, the Company was a single-brand retailer operating under the name of . As such, all corporate overhead costs were reported historically within the operating segment.  As the Companys legal entity structure evolved with the acquisitions of the brand in Fiscal 2005 and the brand in Fiscal 2010, the Company allocated approximately $2 million of corporate overhead costs annually to each of those operating segments from the operating segment. The remainder of the corporate overhead costs continued to be reported primarily within the operating segment.
dressbarn
dressbarn
maurices
Justice
dressbarn
dressbarn
In January 2011, the Company completed an internal corporate reorganization and established a new holding company, named Ascena Retail Group, Inc., to own the interests of each of the , , and brands through wholly owned subsidiaries.  In connection therewith, beginning in Fiscal 2012, the Company implemented a new methodology to allocate corporate overhead costs to each of its operating segments on a reasonable basis.
dressbarn
maurices
Justice
In order to conform to this new cost allocation methodology, the Company has recasted historically reported segment operating results in order to enhance the comparability of its segmental operating performance.  There have been no changes in total net sales or total operating income as a result of this change.
 
 
 
 
